Animal Health Planning and Monitoring

A. Sampling Procedures

Question

 Answer Narrative

A1. Source of samples
A1.1 Does the microbiology laboratory test samples from clinical cases (sick or dead animals) - passive surveillance?
  If Yes, please indicate from which species clinical samples are received for testing. Companion animals (dogs and cats)
Poultry
Pigs
Large ruminants (cattle, buffalo)
  Small ruminants (sheep, goats)
Horses
Aquatic animals (fish, crustaceans, shellfish, frogs)
Wildlife
A1.2 Does the microbiology laboratory test samples from healthy animals - active surveillance, research?
  If Yes, please indicate from which species samples are received for testing. Companion animals (dogs and cats)
Poultry
Pigs
Large ruminants (cattle, buffalo)
Small ruminants (sheep, goats)
Horses
Aquatic animals (fish, crustaceans, shellfish, frogs)
Wildlife
A1.3 Does the microbiology laboratory test food samples?
  If Yes, please indicate which types of food samples are received for testing. Chicken meat or meat products
Eggs or egg products
Pork or pork products
Beef or beef products (cattle, buffalo)
Meat or meat products from small ruminants (goats, sheep)
Milk or milk products (excludes milk received for mastitis testing)
Aquatic animal products (fish, crustaceans, shellfish, frogs)
  If Yes, please indicate what type of tests are performed on food samples. Bacteriology
Chemical residue testing (organic/inorganic)
Antimicrobial residue testing
A1.4 Does the microbiology laboratory test environmental samples? 
  If Yes, please indicate which types of environmental samples are received for testing. Farm (litter, manure, or environment)  
Abattoir/slaughterhouse (litter, manure, or environment)
Animal drinking water
Sewage/Waste water
If Sewage/Waste water samples are received for testing, please indicate the source of the samples.
Surface water (rivers/lake)
Tap water (i.e. from mains supply)
Commercial bottled water
Aquaculture water
  If Yes, please indicate what type of tests are performed on environmental samples. Bacteriology
Chemical residue testing (organic/inorganic)
Antimicrobial residue testing
    Is the environmental sampling linked to an integrated surveillance protocol? If yes, please provide details in narrative box.
A1.5 Does the laboratory test animal feed?
  If Yes, please indicate what type of tests are performed on animal feed. Bacteriology
Chemical residue testing (organic/inorganic)
Antimicrobial residue testing
A2. Sample collection and receival
  Sample collection Are laboratory staff involved with sample collection in the field?
  Have SOPs been developed for AMR-specific active surveillance sampling?
  Does the site have protocols or SOPs for sample receival?
  Does the site have any tools, guidelines or SOPs to capture demographic or epidemiological data when receiving a new sample (please provide details of data collected in narrative column)?
  Has an SOP been developed for internal quality control of sampling processes? 
  Training Have all relevant laboratory staff received training for AMR surveillance-specific SOPs?
If no, or some staff please provide explanation in narrative box.
  Have relevant laboratory staff received up to date training on sampling procedures (biosafety, sample handling and integrity, sample acceptance/rejection criteria etc)?
Please provide details about the training scope and content in the narrative box.
  If no, or some staff please provide explanation in the answer box.  
  Have all relevant staff received training on data management?
If no, or some staff please provide explanation in narrative box.

 

A3 Sample transportation Answer Narrative
Sample transport Have SOPs been developed for sample transport to the laboratory in line with international biosafety standards?
Have all relevant laboratory staff received up to date training for the sample transport SOPs?
If no, or some staff please provide explanation in narrative box.
Are staff involved in sample collection in the field following the SOPs to ensure that samples are transported safely?
If no, or some staff please provide explanation in narrative box.

B. Quality AMR Data Collection

B1. Assessment of bacteriology capacity Answer Narrative
Has an assessment of the bacteriology laboratory capacity been performed in the last two years? 
If yes What assessment tool was used?
Provide the main assessment conclusions (including scoring if relevant) in the narrative box.
Attach the assessment report if available.  
Have corrective actions been implemented following this assessment?
If yes, please provide details in the narrative box.
If no If an assessment is planned, which tool will be used and the timing?

 

B2. Isolate identification and susceptibility testing Answer Narrative
Please indicate if the laboratory can perform culture, ID and AST for any of the following organisms:
Culture and Identification 
 		 Escherichia coli
Salmonella spp.
Staphylococcus aureus 
Campylobacter spp.
Enterocccus spp.
Listeria monocytogenes
Other bacteria (specify)
Is the laboratory using an automated system to perform bacterial identification?
If yes, please indicate which system.
Susceptibility testing  Does the laboratory perform antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST)?
If yes, how does the laboratory perform antimicrobial susceptibility testing?
How does the laboratory perform Minimum Inhibitory Concentration (MIC) testing? 
What standard is being used for AST?
Is the laboratory able to reliably isolate and identify ESBL/AmpC-producing Salmonella spp. and E. coli?
Is the laboratory able to reliably isolate and identify carbapenemase-producing Salmonella spp. and E. coli? 

 

B3. Isolate storage and referral to AMR laboratory  Answer Narrative
Storage of isolates Is there a system for storing bacterial isolates at your laboratory?
If no, please go to Section B4
If yes, how are bacterial isolates stored at the laboratory?
Does the laboratory have SOPs for sample storage?
If freezers are used, is the power supply reliable with a backup generator and UPS?
If freezers are used, are they under a service contract with regular external monitoring of temperature?
If samples are stored, what method is used to link the isolate and the specimen information?
Does the site maintain an up to date inventory of all the isolates stored?
Transport to AMR reference laboratory Are isolates regularly transferred to an AMR reference laboratory?
If yes, how frequently are isolates transferred?

 

B4. Laboratory Quality Management System (LQMS) Answer Narrative
Do you have a Quality Management System in the laboratory?
If no, do you plan to implement a Quality Management System in the laboratory?
Has an assessment of the Quality Management System in your laboratory been performed in the last three years? 
If yes  What assessment tool was used?
Provide a summary of the main observations in the narrative box (including scoring if relevant).
Please attach the assessment report if available

Have corrective actions been implemented following this assessment?
If yes, please describe in narrative box.
Is the microbiology laboratory accredited or following an accreditation process? 
(If yes, please provide accreditation name and date in the narrative box).
Internal Quality Controls (IQC) Are IQC in place for media preparation?
Does the laboratory use reference strains for AST validation? 
Is the laboratory participating in an accredited External Quality Assessment scheme for bacterial identification and antimicrobial susceptibility testing?
If yes  Please indicate which scheme(s) and give details (e.g. proficiency testing scheme or other form of EQA).
Please indicate the date of the latest EQA.
Please provide the main conclusions of the latest EQA including a score.
Please provide the report of the latest EQA, if available.
  Does the laboratory provide EQA to other sites? If yes, please provide details (e.g. provides proficiency testing panel, repeat testing of % of isolates).

 

B5. Training for laboratory staff Answer Narrative
Training for laboratory staff Have relevant laboratory staff received training on the sample processing, organism identification and AST SOPs for the site? If yes, please provide details of SOPs available in the laboratory.
If no, or some staff please provide explanation in the answer box.  
How frequently is training undertaken?
Does the laboratory provide training for bacterial identification/AST to other sites? If yes, please provide details in narrative box.
Are SOPs in place for sample referral and transport to an AMR reference laboratory?
Have relevant laboratory staff received up to date training on these SOPs?
If no, or some staff please provide explanation in narrative box.

 

B6. AMR data analysis and use Answer Narrative
Data management How are laboratory results stored?
Is WHONET used to analyse AST results?
Data analysis and visualisation Does the laboratory produce a report on AMR?
If yes, how often are reports produced?
Data use Are AMR data submitted to a national central database (or equivalent)? If yes, please provide details - data being shared (e.g. number of tests, specimen types, %positive, % SIR, % contamination etc.).
If yes, how frequently are data submitted?
Are any guidelines in place for sharing results with the sample source (i.e. farmers, vets)? If yes, please provide details.
Are data submitted centrally following a round of active surveillance?
Please provide details in the narrative box.
Are AMR data from this site shared with local or international stakeholders? If yes, please provide details in narrative box.
Data linkage How are laboratory and demographic/epidemiology databases linked?
Do the records include unique alphanumeric ID to link bacteriology and demographic/epidemiology data?
If yes, please provide details in narrative box.
Data governance Does the site have a formal AMR data sharing policy or agreement in place with relevant Ministries, other site laboratories or an AMR reference laboratory? If yes, please provide details.
